Introduction¶

we will be using Seattle Airbnb data in this project to analyze it and find any useful insights we can come up with like :

  • Does the prices vary over the year ?
  • what factors may affect the change in prices ?
  • Can we predict prices to inform hosts and travellers?

A look at the data¶

Now after building some intuition about the data let`s start answering our questions¶

Question - 1¶

Does the prices vary over the year ?¶

First lets take care of the 'prices' and 'available' columns from the calender file as we stated above

In [11]:
def clean_float(x):
    '''
    input :
    This function takes a row from a numerical column
    output :
    returns the row value as it should be after removing these '$' , ',' from it if they exist
    '''
    if(type(x) is str):
        x = x.split('$')[1]
        x = x.replace(',','')
    return x

def clean_bool(x):
    '''
    input :
    This function takes row from a boolean column
    output :
    returns the boolean value instead of a char
    '''
    if(x == 'f'):
        return 0
    else:
        return 1

After making those functions let`s apply them

In [12]:
# we will clean the columns first then change its type
cal['price']=cal['price'].apply(clean_float)
cal['price'] = cal['price'].astype(float)
cal['available'] = cal['available'].apply(clean_bool)
cal['available'] = cal['available'].astype('boolean')

we must take care of the date column as we stated above we will convert it to pandas datetime type then extract the months and weekdays from it .

In [15]:
cal['date'] = pd.to_datetime(cal['date'])#change the data type to datetime

cal['day_of_week'] = cal['date'].dt.day_name()#get the day of week

cal['month'] = cal['date'].dt.month_name()# get the month`s name

Now we will make the months in order for the sake of our analysis

In [16]:
cal['month'] = cal['month'].astype('category')#first change the type to category

month_list = ['January','February','March','April','May','June','July','August','September','October','November','December']

cal['month'] = cal['month'].cat.set_categories(month_list,ordered=True)#order the months

Marvellous! Now we are ready to plot the months against the mean of the price

In [17]:

As we see in the summer ,prices on average increase

In [18]:

ax2.set_ylabel('available listings')
ax1.legend(loc=2)

ax2.legend(loc=4)
plt.title('change of prices over the year vs availablity')
plt.show()

Question - 2¶

what factors may affect the change in prices ?¶

We will answer this question from the listings file

But as this part is big we will split it into :

1- categorical features

2- quantitative features

Before we begin, We will use the function we made above to clean the prices column in the listings file (clean_float)

  • we will impute our quantitative features with zero as assuming they dont have it in the case of beds,bedrooms and bathrooms Also assuming they dont require it in case of the weekly price,monthly price,security deposit and cleaning fee

  • But in the case of those columns that have more than 10 percent of it nulls we will make extra indicator column that marks True where the data was missing and False otherwise . In this case we consider the null values as information we do not want to lose

  • we will impute the categorical features with the mode

In [44]:
for i,j in zip(lis_1.columns,lis_1.dtypes):# A loop to handle missing values in our data
    if(lis_1[i].isnull().sum() != 0):
        if(j == 'object'):
            if(lis_1[i].isnull().sum()/lis_1[i].shape[0] > 0.1):#checking if the column has more than of 10% nulls
                lis_1[i+'_na'] = lis_1[i].isnull()#creating extra indicator column
            lis_1[i].fillna(lis_1[i].mode()[0],inplace = True)#imputing the nulls with the mode 
        else:
            if(lis_1[i].isnull().sum()/lis_1[i].shape[0] > 0.1):#checking if the column has more than of 10% nulls
                lis_1[i+'_na'] = lis_1[i].isnull()#creating extra indicator column
            lis_1[i].fillna(lis_1[i].mean(),inplace = True)#imputing the nulls with zero

X_train,X_test,y_train,y_test = train_test_split(X,y,random_state=42)#splitting the data
